In Tamgu, you can create a vector using the following syntax:

vector v = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];

You can also initialize an empty vector:

vector v;

And add elements using the push method:

v.push(10);
v.push(20);

In Tamgu:

- map: An unordered hash map that provides O(1) average lookup time. Keys are not sorted.
  map m = {'a': 1, 'b': 2};

- treemap: An ordered map based on a balanced tree (red-black tree) that maintains keys in sorted order. Lookup time is O(log n).
  treemap tm = {'a': 1, 'b': 2};

Use map for fast lookups when order doesn't matter, and treemap when you need sorted keys.

There are several ways to iterate over a vector in Tamgu:

1. Using a for-in loop:
vector v = [1, 2, 3];
for (x in v)
    println(x);

2. Using an indexed for loop:
for (int i = 0; i < v.size(); i++)
    println(v[i]);

3. Using the map method:
v.map(lambda(x) (println(x)));

