Lambda functions in Tamgu are anonymous functions that can be defined inline. They are useful for short operations:

Syntax: lambda(parameters) (expression)

Example:
vector v = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
vector doubled = v.map(lambda(x) (x * 2));
// Result: [2, 4, 6, 8, 10]

You can also assign lambdas to variables:
function add = lambda(a, b) (a + b);
println(add(3, 4)); // Outputs 7

Tamgu uses try-catch blocks for error handling:

try {
    // Code that might throw an error
    int x = int("not a number");
}
catch(error e) {
    println("Error caught: " + e);
}

You can also throw custom errors:

if (x < 0)
    throw("Value must be positive");

The catch block receives the error as a string.

In Tamgu, 'self' refers to the current instance of an object within a method, similar to 'this' in Java or C++.

Example:
frame MyClass {
    int value;

    function setValue(int v) {
        self.value = v;  // Refers to this instance's value
    }

    function getValue() {
        return self.value;
    }
}

MyClass obj;
obj.setValue(42);
println(obj.getValue()); // Outputs 42

In Tamgu, you can define default parameters by providing values in the function signature:

function greet(string name, string greeting = "Hello") {
    return greeting + ", " + name + "!";
}

println(greet("Alice")); // Outputs: Hello, Alice!
println(greet("Bob", "Hi")); // Outputs: Hi, Bob!

Default parameters must come after required parameters.
